T*
(signal handling on 64-bit x86 Linux . When I undertook this quest, I decided that the easiest) Tj
T*
(way to navigate through the code of the Go runtime was to use the code navigation features) Tj
T*
(exposed by the standard Go language server, gopls . In the process I was surprised by just how) Tj
T*
(good its code navigation was, even in the Go runtime. On Linux, Go's signal handling talks) Tj
T*
(directly to the Linux kernel rather than going through the C library. As you can imagine, this) Tj
T*
(is relatively architecture and Linux specific, as well as being relatively specific to Unix.) Tj
T*
(The result is a tangle of OS and architecture specific code in a variety of signal related) Tj
T*
(files in src/runtime . The first challenge for code navigation is picking out the right ones) Tj
T*
(that apply to the environment you're interested with; in Go this is handled through build tags,) Tj
T*
(which gopls understand. So gopls had no problem navigating from general Unix signal handling to) Tj
T*
(setsig\(\) in Linux-specific code and the 64-bit x86 Linux definition of the struct involved .) Tj
